defs.etymology: Inherited from Proto-Slavic *ničьto, from Proto-Indo-European *ney + *kʷis + *to. The "cz-less" form nic is from Proto-Slavic *ničьso (originally Proto-Slavic *ničeso), an (archaic and synchronically irregular) variant of genitive. Compare with Czech nic, dialectal Ukrainian and Rusyn нич (nyč).
Inherited from Old Polish tamo, from Proto-Slavic *tamo.

examples: Mogę usiąść koło ciebie? ― May I sit next to you?

text: please! Used to make a polite request.
come in! Used to invite someone in to a room.
have at! Used to encourage someone to do something.
pardon? Used to ask someone to repeat what they just said.
hello? Used to answer the phone.
excuse me? Used as a general polite vocative in conjunction with a title.  [+accusative = to whom one is speaking]
you're welcome Used in response to thank you.
here you are Used when handing someone something.
(sometimes duplicated) well, well, well Used in mild surprise to something.
examples: Proszę wyrzucić śmieci. ― Please take out the trash.
Synonym: słucham
Synonyms: halo, słucham

defs.etymology: From przez, due to confusion with the rhyming preposition bez. The two words were and are used interchangeably in various dialects, and in Old Polish przez nearly replaced bez around the 14th-15th century. However, in the written language the earlier distinction ultimately prevailed.

examples: Ja jestem kaleka przez chleba.I am a cripple without livelihood [lit. bread].
I am a cripple without livelihood [lit. bread].
